@node "FileParameter" "FILE Parameter"
Name of file to watch

This parameter specifies the name of the file you want FileWatcher to watch.
If the file is not in the current directory, you must specify it's path.
@endnode

@node "FileIconParameter" "FILEICON Parameter"
Icon Name for nonzero byte file

This parameter specifies the name of the icon you want FileWatcher to show
when the file is greater than zero bytes long.  If the icon you want to use is
not in the current directory, you must specify it's path.

NOTE: do not specify .info as part of the filename, it will be added
@endnode

@node "NoFileIconParameter" "NOFILEICON Parameter"
Icon Name for zero byte or nonexistent file

This parameter specifies the name of the icon you want FileWatcher to show
when the file either does not exists or is zero bytes long.  If the icon you
want to use is not in the current directory, you must specify it's path.

NOTE: do not specify .info as part of the filename, it will be added
@endnode

@node "NameParameter" "NAME Parameter"
Name to show under the AppIcon

This parameter allows you to specify the name you want to appear under the
AppIcon If you don't specify one, the default will be "FileWatcher"
@endnode

@node "CMDParameter" "CMD Parameter"
Name of the command to run

This parameter allows you to specify the command you wish to run when the
AppIcon is double clicked on.  The command is currently run with a stack of
4000, however in some future version you will be able to specify the size of
the stack to use.  If the command you want to use is not on your path when you
run FileWatcher, you must specify it's path.
@endnode

@node "Stopping" "Stopping FileWatcher"
To stop FileWatcher, all you have to do is send it a Control C.  You can use
the AmigaDOS break command to do this if you ran it in the background, or any
one of the Intuition based tools that can send a Control C to a process (I use
Scout 2.2 myself).
@endnode

@node "Changes" "Changes"
0.2 Added ability to use Tool Types for startup parameters

0.1 Original Release
@endnode

